                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Pra[e]da[e] divisio mixta: maxima pars Qua[e]stori; minor militi data. Romana Oeconomia publica: s[upr]a, i[nfr]a. Diuisio Oligarchica magis, 
                        qu&agrave;m Democratica: aut etiam Democratica, ad publicos, non privatos vsus. Quid mirum, si in Monarchia, plus Qua[e]stori, qu&agrave;m Militi distribuatur? 
                        Stipendium, Militis merces; vt operetur Regi conductori, non sibi: nisi quaten&ugrave;s aliqua incidunt priuata spolia, tolerata magis, qu&agrave;m concessa: 
                        aut quaten&ugrave;s Dux interdum aliquid indulget animandi causa. In Monarchia, regula est; Omnis Honor, et Qua[e]stus Regis: Officia et pra[e]mia, 
                        non debita, sed favores, et indulgentia[e]. Prudens Rex respiciet Virtutem; et Meritorum habebit rationem honorificam.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="pra[e]da[e] diuisio"/>
                    <internal_ref text="s[upr]a">
                        <target filename="00000071.xml" book_id="PrincetonPA6452" text="[49]"/>
                    </internal_ref>
                    <internal_ref text="i[nfr]a">
                        <target filename="00000235.xml" book_id="PrincetonPA6452" text="[213]"/>
                    </internal_ref>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>A varied distribution of booty. The bigger part is given to the quaestor, the smaller one to the soldiers. The Roman public administration, 
                above, below. Rather an oligarchical than a democratic distribution, or even democratic for public, not private benefit. Small wonder, if in a monarchy 
                more is given to the quaestor than to the soldiers! There is pay, the soldier's salary, so that he is at work for the king as his employer, not for himself; 
                except insofar as some private spoils happen to come available, tolerated rather than granted, or insofar as a leader occasionally grants some favour 
                for the sake of animating. In a monarchy the rule is: all honor and all profit is the Kingâ€™s; services and rewards are favours and kindnesses, 
                not obligations. A prudent king will have regard for virtue and will have an honorable system of rewards.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
